The Al-Anon Family Groups are a fellowship of relatives and friends of alcoholics who share their experience, strength and hope in order to solve their common problems. We believe alcoholism is a family illness, and that changed attitudes can aid recovery. Al-Anon has but one purpose: to help friends and families of alcoholics. We do this by practicing the Twelve Steps, by welcoming and giving comfort to families and friends of alcoholics, and by giving understanding and encouragement to the alcoholic. Whether the alcoholic is still drinking or not, Al-Anon offers hope and recovery to all people affected by the alcoholism of a loved one or friend.

title: Mummies: Culture, Science and People From Around the World
description:
UCF has a unique opportunity to hear from Dr. Heather
Gill-Frerking, director of Science & Education for the Mummies of the World
traveling exhibition. On Wednesday, June 10, at 7 p.m.at the UCF Main Campus,
Psychology Building, Room 108, Dr. Gill-Frerking will present "Mummies:
Culture, Science and People From Around the World." The Mummies of the
World exhibition will open at the Orlando Science Center on June 13.

Mummies of the World is one of the largest
exhibitions of mummies and related artifacts ever assembled. This
groundbreaking exhibition bridges the gap between past and present, showing how
science can shed light on history, the study of medicine and cultures around
the world. Featuring a never-before-seen collection of objects and specimens,
including real human and animal mummies and related artifacts from South
America, Europe and Egypt, Mummies of the World also demonstrates that
mummification - both through natural and intentional processes - has taken
place all over the globe, from the hot desert sands of South America to remote
European bogs. To learn more, visit mummiesoftheworld.com.

In the presentation at UCF, Dr. Gill-Frerking will
explore some of the cultural and environmental reasons that bodies may
preserve, and share some of my recent research on mummies from South America,
Europe and Egypt. Come and hear the stories of the German Baron with leather
boots, the South American woman with tattoos, the infant from ancient Egypt who
was older than first believed, the Iron Age body from northern Germany that had
been misinterpreted for more than 50 years, and many other interesting people
of the past. > For more information, visit cos.ucf.edu/mummies.

title: UCF Alumni: UCF MedTalk
description:
TheÂ UCF College of MedicineÂ andÂ UCF Alumni AssociationÂ invite you to UCF MedTalk. Dr. Griffith ParksÂ will discussÂ â€œThe Upshot on Viruses and Vaccines.â€Â Learn from this leading scientist who'sÂ research interests include developing novel vaccines for viral diseases and the use of viruses for the targeted killing of tumor cells. Dr. Parks will discuss whyÂ viruses are among the most deadly known diseases of mankind, including smallpox, measles virus and influenza virus. While there have been fantastic successes in the use of vaccines to combat many of these diseases, there is also a rise in the number of people that are not vaccinated against viruses.

The talk will provide basic information that addresses:Â
  • What is a virus and why are they hard to control?
  • How are vaccines made and why do I need to get some vaccines annually?
  • Where are all these new viruses coming from?
What is UCF MedTalk?Whether youâ€™re a College of Medicine grad, or just a curious Knight who enjoys learning more about current and innovative issues in medicine, all are encouraged to join this unique conversation. This special series of informal talks includes a casual meeting place, plain language and comfortable atmosphere for everyone. Each researcher or physician will give a brief presentation, followed by a Q&A session.Â About the SpeakerDr. Parks received his Ph.D. in biochemistry from the University of Wisconsin-Madison and was an American Cancer Society Fellow at Northwestern University.Prior to moving to UCF, he was Professor and Chairman of the Department of Microbiology and Immunology at the Wake Forest School of Medicine and founding Director of the WFU Vaccine Center.Â Space is limited and is on a first come first serve basis. One round of free appetizers and drinks are generously provided by our sponsors: FAIRWINDS Credit Union and DownTown PourHouse.

In the last five years, TEAM WLSL has set five Guinness World Records (GWR) for the Worldâ€™s Largest Swimming Lessonâ„¢, with 36,564 swimmers from 22 countries participating in 2014. More importantly, our team effort has spread the vital message Swimming Lessons Save Livesâ„¢ through more than 150 million media impressions.Â

Since our first event in 2010, more than 120,000 people have participated in WLSL events and millions and millions of individuals have learned about the vital importance of teaching children to swim to help prevent the second leading cause of accidental death for kids 1-14.Â

We are so grateful to all the aquatic centers, pools and waterparks around the globe that have hosted WLSL events and to our participants, supporting organizations, sponsors and the media that help spread this vital message.

title: Invasive Lionfish Collecting and Handling Workshop
description:
Reef Environmental Education Foundation, the University of Central Florida, the Marine Discovery Center, and Sea Dogs Dive Center invite you to learn about the invasive lionfish and ways to get involved.

When: Thursday, June 18, 2015
Where: UCF Biology Field Research Center, Building 92, Ara Drive, Orlando, FL 32826
Time: 6-8PM
Cost: Free and open to the public
Speaker: Elizabeth Underwood, REEF Lionfish Program Coordinator
Who: Divers, fishers, and ocean enthusiasts encouraged to attend

Workshop topics include background of the invasion, lionfish biology, ecological impacts, current research findings, collecting tools and techniques, market development and ways to get involved. REEF is a grassroots non-profit organization committed to ocean conservation and education. The REEF team conducts workshops to educate resource managers, divers, fishers and marine enthusiasts. By engaging stakeholders, REEF seeks to reduce negative ecological impacts.

Lionfish Hunting Dives will be hosted by Sea Dogs Dive Center in New Smyrna Beach on June 19th. Book your spot with them (386-424-1644) or go out on your own boat and remove lionfish on June 19th. Then join us at the Marine Discovery Center in New Smyrna Beach at 4pm for a weigh-in, lionfish cook-out and more!

Registration is required! Register here: www.REEF.org/lionfish/workshops

Our fellowship focuses primarily on recovery from the disease of addiction. Anyone may join us regardless of age, race, sexual identity, creed, religion or lack of religion. Â

title: Al-Anon: Serenity Now
description:
This meeting is held every Monday (unless otherwise noted on the UCF calendar) from 7pm to 8pm on the UCF Main Campus inside the COUNSELING AND PSYCHOLOGICAL SERVICES building.

The Al-Anon Family Groups are a fellowship of relatives and friends of alcoholics who share their experience, strength and hope in order to solve their common problems. We believe alcoholism is a family illness, and that changed attitudes can aid recovery. Al-Anon has but one purpose: to help friends and families of alcoholics. We do this by practicing the Twelve Steps, by welcoming and giving comfort to families and friends of alcoholics, and by giving understanding and encouragement to the alcoholic. Whether the alcoholic is still drinking or not, Al-Anon offers hope and recovery to all people affected by the alcoholism of a loved one or friend.

For more information about this meeting visit www.hs.ucf.edu/crc or call the Al-Anon Family Groups Helpline at (800) 344-2666.

description:
